04415nam a2200577Ia 9780674043404DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20091995mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740434047 a10.4159/97806740434042doi  a(DE-B1597)585462  a(OCoLC)1294426543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQL568.A6 ǂb S445 1995eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a595.7990451  aES 1782rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27815:1 aSeeley, Thomas D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wisdom of the Hive :bThe Social Physiology of Honey Bee Colonies /cThomas D. Seeley. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (317 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPART I. INTRODUCTION -- t1. The Issues -- t2. The Honey Bee Colony -- t3. The Foraging Abilities of a Colony -- tPART II. EXPERIMENTAL ANALYSIS -- t4. Methods and Equipment -- t5. Allocation of Labor among Forage Sites -- t6. Coordination of Nectar Collecting and Nectar Processing -- t7. Regulation of Comb Construction -- t8. Regulation of Pollen Collection -- t9. Regulation of Water Collection -- tPART III. OVERVIEW -- t10. The Main Features of Colony Organization -- t11. Enduring Lessons from the Hive -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about the inner workings of one of nature’s most complex animal societies: the honey bee colony. It describes and illustrates the results of more than fifteen years of elegant experimental studies conducted by the author. In his investigations, Thomas Seeley has sought the answer to the question of how a colony of bees is organized to gather its resources. The results of his research—including studies of the shaking signal, tremble dance, and waggle dance, and other, more subtle means by which information is exchanged among bees—offer the clearest, most detailed picture available of how a highly integrated animal society works. By showing how several thousand bees function together as an integrated whole to collect the nectar, pollen, and water that sustain the life of the hive, Seeley sheds light on one of the central puzzles of biology: how units at one level of organization can work together to form a higher-level entity.In explaining why a hive is organized the way it is, Seeley draws on the literature of molecular biology, cell biology, animal and human sociology, economics, and operations research. He compares the honey bee colony to other functionally organized groups: multicellular organisms, colonies of marine invertebrates, and human societies. All highly cooperative groups share basic problems: of allocating their members among tasks so that more urgent needs are met before less urgent ones, and of coordinating individual actions into a coherent whole. By comparing such systems in different species, Seeley argues, we can deepen our understanding of the mechanisms that make close cooperation a reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674043404?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674043404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674043404/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles